1
00:00:03,046 --> 00:00:05,465
Sales for the first generation
of Ava clones have been

2
00:00:05,548 --> 00:00:06,883
through the roof as predicted.

3
00:00:06,966 --> 00:00:09,928
My dream of an Ava in every home
and business has become a reality.

4
00:00:10,011 --> 00:00:12,013
How wonderful. Congratulations, sir.

5
00:00:15,683 --> 00:00:17,060
Sir...

6
00:00:19,145 --> 00:00:22,106
I was going to wait until after
the investment meeting to mention this.

7
00:00:23,066 --> 00:00:25,735
But I think it's time you told me
about this mystery project

8
00:00:25,818 --> 00:00:26,818
you've been working on.

9
00:00:27,487 --> 00:00:29,739
It's just that
you've diverted billions into it,

10
00:00:29,822 --> 00:00:32,992
and I really feel like it's time I knew
what the project was all about.

11
00:00:33,368 --> 00:00:34,728
Where do you think I'm taking you?

12
00:00:36,079 --> 00:00:37,580
Ta-da!

13
00:00:41,376 --> 00:00:44,254
It's called a <i>Wa verider.</i>

14
00:00:44,546 --> 00:00:45,588
<i>Wa verider?</i>

15
00:00:46,047 --> 00:00:47,382
Oh!

16
00:00:47,465 --> 00:00:50,843
Because it's shaped like a boat?
Like it rides on the waves?

17
00:00:51,469 --> 00:00:53,096
No, though it can go underwater.

18
00:00:53,179 --> 00:00:54,305
But never mind that.

19
00:00:54,389 --> 00:00:57,517
<i>Wa verider</i> is what it's called in the
futuristic blueprints I was given.

20
00:00:58,685 --> 00:00:59,978
It's a Timeship.

21
00:01:02,689 --> 00:01:03,856
<i>Wa verider?</i>

22
00:01:04,482 --> 00:01:07,026
Are you married to that name,
or can we still pitch on it?

23
00:01:09,028 --> 00:01:10,572
Welcome to the bridge.

24
00:01:10,822 --> 00:01:12,991
The nerve center of the entire ship.

25
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:16,244
Not the most efficient use
of space, though.

26
00:01:16,327 --> 00:01:18,121
Maybe it could double
as a conference room.

27
00:01:18,204 --> 00:01:21,374
And now it's time for you
to see an old friend.

28
00:01:22,166 --> 00:01:23,167
Gideon.

29
00:01:23,459 --> 00:01:24,586
Time to wake up.

30
00:01:26,796 --> 00:01:27,797
There you are.

31
00:01:28,214 --> 00:01:30,859
My transfer to the ship's
mainframe appears to be a success.

32
00:01:30,883 --> 00:01:31,883
You remember Gideon?

33
00:01:31,926 --> 00:01:33,219
Oh, yes. Her.

34
00:01:34,304 --> 00:01:36,180
Welcome to your new home, Gideon.

35
00:01:36,723 --> 00:01:39,475
So much more space to roam
than that tiny hard drive you were in.

36
00:01:40,226 --> 00:01:42,270
Take a couple laps around,
stretch your legs.

37
00:01:42,353 --> 00:01:44,272
You have vantage points
all over the ship.

38
00:01:51,154 --> 00:01:52,840
You followed
my exact specifications,

39
00:01:52,864 --> 00:01:55,199
but I don't have
any visual access in Section A2.

40
00:01:55,283 --> 00:01:57,452
Section A2 is the only bathroom
on the ship.

41
00:01:57,660 --> 00:02:00,913
I can't have you spying on me in there.
A man needs his privacy.

42
00:02:00,997 --> 00:02:01,997
Yes.

43
00:02:02,415 --> 00:02:04,042
Sir, as impressive as this ship is,

44
00:02:04,125 --> 00:02:05,765
how does it relate to
the Ava Corp mission

45
00:02:05,793 --> 00:02:08,838
of improving people's lives
through clone technology exactly?

46
00:02:08,921 --> 00:02:13,009
Well, I'm simply expanding our mission
by adding time travel to the mix.

47
00:02:14,135 --> 00:02:16,804
But the true perk of this ship
is to finally get revenge

48
00:02:17,013 --> 00:02:18,765
on those time travelers who abducted me,

49
00:02:18,848 --> 00:02:21,976
used me for my genius
and then messed with my mind.

50
00:02:22,810 --> 00:02:25,122
May I remind you that
a Time Master's number one duty is

51
00:02:25,146 --> 00:02:28,399
to protect the timeline from any
and all threats to its integrity.

52
00:02:28,483 --> 00:02:31,903
Yes. Yes, Gideon. That's a given,
considering the job title.

53
00:02:32,487 --> 00:02:33,488
Time Master.

54
00:02:33,988 --> 00:02:36,628
And before we start,
you must take the Time Masters' oath.

55
00:02:37,408 --> 00:02:40,745
"I swear to protect and defend
the integrity of the timeline

56
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:43,122
with all my ability
until the end of my days."

57
00:02:44,082 --> 00:02:45,333
Congratulations.

58
00:02:45,416 --> 00:02:47,585
You are now Time Master
of this <i>Wa verider.</i>

59
00:02:47,669 --> 00:02:48,669
Great.

60
00:02:49,337 --> 00:02:52,507
Let's set sail on our maiden voyage

61
00:02:54,342 --> 00:02:55,843
and protect the timeline

62
00:02:56,844 --> 00:02:58,513
from those damn Legends.

63
00:03:22,912 --> 00:03:25,623
The machine is ruined,
wrecked, absolutely kaput.

64
00:03:25,707 --> 00:03:27,507
- And all because of you lot!
- Okay, hold on.

65
00:03:27,625 --> 00:03:29,385
How is it our fault
we didn't land in Tahiti?

66
00:03:29,585 --> 00:03:32,171
Because it wasn't designed
to take all you people.

67
00:03:32,255 --> 00:03:35,425
The excess weight. It threw it all off!

68
00:03:35,717 --> 00:03:38,177
Okay, so I'm guessing we have
no idea what year we're in?

69
00:03:38,886 --> 00:03:41,639
The chrono-gauge and the ignition coil
are both sequenced

70
00:03:41,764 --> 00:03:44,164
to the directional compass,
which was damaged in the landing.

71
00:03:44,225 --> 00:03:45,225
So no, I don't think so.

72
00:03:45,727 --> 00:03:47,037
Well, that doesn't sound too good.

73
00:03:47,061 --> 00:03:48,980
But, hey, who needs a chrono-gauge

74
00:03:49,063 --> 00:03:50,857
when you have two ex-Time Bureau agents

75
00:03:50,940 --> 00:03:52,942
with extensive historical knowledge?
Gary?

76
00:03:53,025 --> 00:03:54,025
That's right, Ava.

77
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:57,071
And based on the local flora,

78
00:03:58,030 --> 00:03:59,830
there's a chance
we're in the prehistoric era.

79
00:04:00,783 --> 00:04:02,143
Give or take a few thousand years.

80
00:04:02,952 --> 00:04:03,992
Maybe we'll see dinosaurs.

81
00:04:04,036 --> 00:04:06,080
You better hope
we don't see a dinosaur, Gary.

82
00:04:06,748 --> 00:04:08,374
Okay, so it looks like we're

83
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:10,752
making this prehistoric forest
home for a while.

84
00:04:10,835 --> 00:04:13,171
So let's get comfortable, gang.

85
00:04:13,254 --> 00:04:15,798
Guys, come on. This team
has been stranded more times

86
00:04:15,882 --> 00:04:18,009
than I can count
and in way worse places than this.

87
00:04:18,801 --> 00:04:19,844
She's right.

88
00:04:21,095 --> 00:04:24,015
I know nothing has gone our way
since we left Odessa, but...

89
00:04:26,476 --> 00:04:27,477
they're gonna get better.

90
00:04:27,560 --> 00:04:28,978
- Yeah.
- Okay?

91
00:04:29,270 --> 00:04:32,398
All right. So, you are the only one
that can fix this time machine.

92
00:04:32,899 --> 00:04:34,817
If you can repair
that directional compass,

93
00:04:34,942 --> 00:04:36,152
are we back in business?

94
00:04:36,277 --> 00:04:38,917
It would be a difficult task,
even if we did have the proper tools.

95
00:04:39,113 --> 00:04:40,239
- I can help.
- Me too.

96
00:04:41,449 --> 00:04:44,035
You got two techies
at your disposal, my man.

97
00:04:44,452 --> 00:04:47,872
Just some peace to be able
to get on with my work is all I ask.

98
00:04:47,955 --> 00:04:51,209
You know, I will venture off
and maybe find some lodestone,

99
00:04:51,292 --> 00:04:53,520
or some other magnetic material
which conducts electricity

100
00:04:53,544 --> 00:04:55,064
and, well, then I can fix the compass.

101
00:04:57,048 --> 00:04:59,842
Hey, maybe you and B
should go with Dr. Cranky.

102
00:04:59,926 --> 00:05:00,927
We'll set up camp here.

103
00:05:01,219 --> 00:05:02,637
Mmm-hmm. All over it.

104
00:05:03,346 --> 00:05:05,186
Hey, look. I know
we didn't really get a chance

105
00:05:05,264 --> 00:05:06,825
to talk about the whole moving in thing.

106
00:05:06,849 --> 00:05:07,934
No, it's totally cool.

107
00:05:08,726 --> 00:05:10,686
As usual, we have bigger fish to fry.

108
00:05:10,812 --> 00:05:12,480
I know, but, you know,

109
00:05:12,563 --> 00:05:15,483
moving into a spiritual realm
there's a lot to take in.

110
00:05:15,608 --> 00:05:17,648
I just want to make sure
you're not... freaking out.

111
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:20,404
Freak out? Me? No. I'm super chill.

112
00:05:21,614 --> 00:05:25,910
I am, however,
concerned about our captains.

113
00:05:26,786 --> 00:05:28,704
Yeah, well. Good luck with that.

114
00:05:29,163 --> 00:05:30,163
- Bye.
- What?

115
00:05:30,206 --> 00:05:31,541
- Yeah.
- Miss you.

116
00:05:31,624 --> 00:05:32,625
Bye.

117
00:05:34,252 --> 00:05:35,837
Psst! Hey! You two.

118
00:05:35,920 --> 00:05:37,046
Come here. Shut up.

119
00:05:38,464 --> 00:05:40,341
Do either one of you
know how to read lips?

120
00:05:41,634 --> 00:05:43,970
Who needs to read lips
when Spooner can read minds?

121
00:05:44,136 --> 00:05:45,263
Mmm.

122
00:05:49,016 --> 00:05:50,393
Phew!

123
00:05:50,476 --> 00:05:53,521
I'm getting some major anxiety vibes
from Sara right now.

124
00:05:53,938 --> 00:05:56,774
Yeah, and I don't need superpowers
to see that Ava is cracking.

125
00:05:56,858 --> 00:05:58,898
They're just stressing
each other out at this point.

126
00:05:58,943 --> 00:06:00,903
Okay, so let's separate them
so they each

127
00:06:00,987 --> 00:06:02,587
don't have a complete
and total meltdown.

128
00:06:02,989 --> 00:06:03,989
Okay?

129
00:06:04,824 --> 00:06:07,410
Hey there, <i>jefa</i>. How about
we hunt down some dinner?

130
00:06:07,577 --> 00:06:09,620
Yeah, let's go stab something.

131
00:06:11,622 --> 00:06:13,666
Wanna go for a hike?
We could get some firewood.

132
00:06:13,791 --> 00:06:15,209
Yeah, I would love a multi-task.

133
00:06:16,168 --> 00:06:17,168
Great.

134
00:06:20,673 --> 00:06:22,425
- So...
- Oh, Gary.

135
00:06:22,508 --> 00:06:24,343
You and Zari. Saw you talking.

136
00:06:25,553 --> 00:06:26,637
And?

137
00:06:27,513 --> 00:06:29,199
She asked me to move in with her
in the Totem.

138
00:06:29,223 --> 00:06:31,100
Oh, that's great!

139
00:06:33,269 --> 00:06:34,770
That's not, not great?

140
00:06:35,813 --> 00:06:38,693
Sorry, the more handsome the face,
the harder it is for me to get a read.

141
00:06:38,774 --> 00:06:40,276
All right, just back up.

142
00:06:40,359 --> 00:06:41,652
It's just...

143
00:06:41,944 --> 00:06:43,664
I haven't spent that much time
in the Totem.

144
00:06:44,113 --> 00:06:46,365
She sprung it on me
before we time jumped here,

145
00:06:46,782 --> 00:06:48,622
so I really haven't had
a chance to process it.

146
00:06:49,410 --> 00:06:51,829
But, Nate, the Totem seems quite small.
How'd you get inside?

147
00:06:52,830 --> 00:06:54,474
Are you and Zari gonna live
in a house together?

148
00:06:54,498 --> 00:06:56,560
Will there be pie? Because I really like
strawberry rhubarb.

149
00:06:56,584 --> 00:06:59,264
- I love strawberry rhubarb.
- We need to focus on today's problems.

150
00:06:59,462 --> 00:07:03,841
Okay? How about you guys forage
for some food? Leaves, nuts, berries.

151
00:07:03,925 --> 00:07:05,509
Anything we can eat, okay? Go.

152
00:07:05,676 --> 00:07:06,677
- Okay.
- Go.

153
00:07:06,844 --> 00:07:07,887
- Okay.
- Okay.

154
00:07:08,846 --> 00:07:11,486
You sure you don't want me
to stick around? Be your sounding board?

155
00:07:11,849 --> 00:07:12,975
- We can...
- Gary.

156
00:07:14,185 --> 00:07:17,521
You will not be my sounding board today.
Okay? Thank you.

157
00:07:18,105 --> 00:07:19,106
- Okay.
- Go on.

158
00:07:23,903 --> 00:07:26,423
Well, at least these two ding dongs
can't screw anything up here

159
00:07:26,489 --> 00:07:28,074
that will attract the evil <i>Wa verider.</i>

160
00:07:37,458 --> 00:07:39,058
Check out that view
of the temporal zone.

161
00:07:39,752 --> 00:07:42,046
- Worth a million bucks. Huh?
- Mmm.

162
00:07:42,296 --> 00:07:44,590
Considering this ship costs
many thousand times more,

163
00:07:44,674 --> 00:07:47,152
I'm not sure how the board's gonna feel
about your investment, sir.

164
00:07:47,176 --> 00:07:49,804
There's one thing you just can't put
a price on, assistant Ava.

165
00:07:49,887 --> 00:07:51,597
- Hmm?
- Revenge.

166
00:07:51,722 --> 00:07:52,723
Ah.

167
00:07:52,807 --> 00:07:54,284
Captain, we're getting an alert

168
00:07:54,308 --> 00:07:57,103
of several anachronisms
in 1925 Odessa, Texas.

169
00:07:57,395 --> 00:07:58,562
Hmm.

170
00:07:58,646 --> 00:08:00,398
"Captain." I like that.

171
00:08:00,856 --> 00:08:02,650
Odessa. Wait a second. Texas.

172
00:08:02,984 --> 00:08:05,653
That's where the Legends took me.
Gideon, you found them!

173
00:08:06,070 --> 00:08:07,071
Engage weapons systems.

174
00:08:07,154 --> 00:08:08,590
I'm gonna bomb
the living daylights out of them.

175
00:08:08,614 --> 00:08:10,825
I am advising against
this course of action.

176
00:08:11,033 --> 00:08:13,261
How else am I supposed to
wipe them off the face of the earth?

177
00:08:13,285 --> 00:08:15,013
Eliminating the Legends
in this blunt manner

178
00:08:15,037 --> 00:08:16,872
will cause excessive collateral damage.

179
00:08:17,039 --> 00:08:18,874
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

180
00:08:19,291 --> 00:08:20,418
Your warning is duly noted.

181
00:08:30,594 --> 00:08:32,722
Yes!

182
00:08:32,972 --> 00:08:36,058
Those bastards finally got
what they deserved!

183
00:08:36,517 --> 00:08:38,019
It's a lot easier than I expected.

184
00:08:39,812 --> 00:08:41,272
Can we please go home now, sir?

185
00:08:41,731 --> 00:08:44,108
No, the captain's impulsive
and violent actions

186
00:08:44,191 --> 00:08:46,991
guarantee ripple effects in the timeline
that we will have to clean up.

187
00:08:47,528 --> 00:08:50,823
More precise measures must be taken when
dealing with threats moving forward.

188
00:08:50,948 --> 00:08:54,577
Trust me, this was the only way
to deal with those Legends.

189
00:08:55,202 --> 00:08:57,038
And if any ripples arise, we'll just use

190
00:08:57,121 --> 00:09:00,458
our brand new Timeship
to smooth them out.

191
00:09:08,299 --> 00:09:09,467
Hey, buddy.

192
00:09:10,134 --> 00:09:11,218
Got your coat.

193
00:09:11,969 --> 00:09:13,012
You okay?

194
00:09:13,721 --> 00:09:17,308
Listen. We don't really
have time for a rest stop.

195
00:09:18,017 --> 00:09:21,103
We need to find the materials you need
to fix your time machine. Yeah?

196
00:09:21,604 --> 00:09:22,998
You really don't understand, do you?

197
00:09:23,022 --> 00:09:25,066
I just told you lot
what you wanted to hear.

198
00:09:25,983 --> 00:09:28,944
In reality, there is no point
in fixing the wretched machine.

199
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:33,280
Sure, there was
a little problem with the dismount,

200
00:09:33,324 --> 00:09:35,701
but your invention actually worked.

201
00:09:35,993 --> 00:09:39,955
Yeah. So, why don't we
put our shoes back on

202
00:09:40,039 --> 00:09:42,958
and we can help you find magnetite
or whatever mineral it is

203
00:09:43,042 --> 00:09:44,919
you need to get your invention

204
00:09:45,002 --> 00:09:46,003
back up and running.

205
00:09:46,170 --> 00:09:48,010
To fix the machine,
we need to fix the compass,

206
00:09:48,089 --> 00:09:49,983
and in order to do that,
we need magnetic material,

207
00:09:50,007 --> 00:09:51,175
which conducts electricity.

208
00:09:51,258 --> 00:09:54,887
And I doubt that you would even know
what to look for, and either way,

209
00:09:54,970 --> 00:09:57,690
it's not about fixing the machine
or not fixing the machine, you see,

210
00:09:57,723 --> 00:09:59,683
because no matter what I do,
I'm always meant...

211
00:10:00,976 --> 00:10:01,977
to fail.

212
00:10:03,437 --> 00:10:04,563
You see, my machine,

213
00:10:05,815 --> 00:10:07,608
it was meant to explode.

214
00:10:08,317 --> 00:10:10,504
Yeah, but it didn't explode.
We're alive and we're here.

215
00:10:10,528 --> 00:10:13,823
Yes, yes, we're here.
We're here in the middle of nowhere!

216
00:10:15,908 --> 00:10:17,034
My divine mission,

217
00:10:18,202 --> 00:10:19,453
derailed once again.

218
00:10:21,705 --> 00:10:23,457
There is no fighting God's will, my boy.

219
00:10:24,542 --> 00:10:26,001
Being here is proof of that.

220
00:10:28,087 --> 00:10:29,630
You lot might as well get comfortable.

221
00:10:31,632 --> 00:10:32,925
We're not going anywhere,

222
00:10:33,926 --> 00:10:36,720
because nowhere is exactly
where I'm meant to be.

223
00:10:53,154 --> 00:10:56,073
Astounding. You can't even tell
that Gideon fabricated this food.

224
00:10:56,866 --> 00:10:58,701
Fabricated? From what?

225
00:10:59,577 --> 00:11:02,297
We've received an alert
about a disturbance in the timeline.

226
00:11:02,746 --> 00:11:05,541
Fun! Which thrilling time period
are we headed to next?

227
00:11:05,875 --> 00:11:08,085
- 1925.
- Ooh!

228
00:11:09,170 --> 00:11:10,713
Weren't we just in 1925?

229
00:11:10,796 --> 00:11:11,964
That is quite a coincidence.

230
00:11:12,047 --> 00:11:13,507
What's the disturbance, Gideon?

231
00:11:14,049 --> 00:11:15,649
J. Edgar Hoover
has disappeared,

232
00:11:15,759 --> 00:11:18,095
and unfortunately,
it is not a coincidence.

233
00:11:18,679 --> 00:11:22,016
My calculations confirm your attack
on the Legends caused this aberration.

234
00:11:24,935 --> 00:11:28,230
Well, if Hoover is the problem,

235
00:11:29,064 --> 00:11:30,608
then Hoover is the solution.

236
00:11:32,109 --> 00:11:33,589
We'll just use my clone technology...

237
00:11:34,695 --> 00:11:36,071
And make a clone of Mr. Hoover.

238
00:11:36,155 --> 00:11:38,035
So we can plop them right back
into the timeline

239
00:11:38,115 --> 00:11:40,367
- and no one will even know.
- Mmm-hmm.

240
00:11:40,659 --> 00:11:43,037
Clones are still human
and humans are fallible.

241
00:11:43,370 --> 00:11:45,206
Remember, one of your Ava clones

242
00:11:45,289 --> 00:11:47,666
eventually became a Legend
and helped kidnap you.

243
00:11:47,750 --> 00:11:48,751
Okay, Gideon.

244
00:11:48,834 --> 00:11:51,837
Absolutely no need to lump us all in
with that horrible traitor.

245
00:11:51,921 --> 00:11:54,590
Mr. Hoover is integral
to many seminal moments in history.

246
00:11:54,673 --> 00:11:57,801
