00:25:42,625 --> 00:25:45,920
Now, I think it's time
you take me back home.

495
00:25:46,671 --> 00:25:47,797
Home?

496
00:25:48,006 --> 00:25:49,507
You're a Time Master now.

497
00:25:50,592 --> 00:25:52,302
This is your home.

498
00:26:12,781 --> 00:26:13,823
<i>Hello?</i>

499
00:26:15,325 --> 00:26:16,969
Who the hell is this?
Where's receptionist Ava?

500
00:26:16,993 --> 00:26:18,012
<i>Who the hell is this?</i>

501
00:26:18,036 --> 00:26:19,204
It's me, Bishop.

502
00:26:20,705 --> 00:26:21,705
Is this a prank?

503
00:26:22,165 --> 00:26:23,583
Is that you, voice actor Ava?

504
00:26:23,666 --> 00:26:25,418
Your impressions are uncanny.

505
00:26:25,502 --> 00:26:27,629
No, listen. It's Bishop.

506
00:26:27,712 --> 00:26:29,297
Okay? This is getting annoying.

507
00:26:29,380 --> 00:26:30,500
How did you get this number?

508
00:26:30,799 --> 00:26:32,175
Why do you sound exactly like me?

509
00:26:32,467 --> 00:26:34,886
No, you sound exactly like me.
It's like someone...

510
00:26:41,810 --> 00:26:43,853
No, no, no, no, no.

511
00:26:46,606 --> 00:26:48,108
Gideon made a copy of me.

512
00:26:49,692 --> 00:26:50,777
Of me?

513
00:26:51,569 --> 00:26:54,155
How dare she?
There could only be one me.

514
00:26:57,242 --> 00:26:59,744
Wait a second,
this can't be my actual to-do list.

515
00:27:00,495 --> 00:27:02,247
I pay someone to kidnap a superhero

516
00:27:02,372 --> 00:27:04,624
and take them
to a planet called Pliny X19?

517
00:27:05,208 --> 00:27:06,417
What the hell's a Necrian?

518
00:27:07,293 --> 00:27:08,503
The Fountain of Imperium?

519
00:27:10,338 --> 00:27:11,756
I try to destroy the world?

520
00:27:13,341 --> 00:27:14,717
And the Legends are the good guys?

521
00:27:18,346 --> 00:27:23,309
They kidnapped me to give me a chance
to redeem myself, to save the world.

522
00:27:24,978 --> 00:27:25,979
Oh, no.

523
00:27:26,062 --> 00:27:27,414
I've been wrong about them
this whole time?

524
00:27:27,438 --> 00:27:29,958
You should not be looking
at that information, Captain.

525
00:27:30,275 --> 00:27:31,317
Tell me it's not true.

526
00:27:32,861 --> 00:27:35,780
Tell me I don't become a bad guy.

527
00:27:35,989 --> 00:27:39,159
Having information about your
own future can be extremely dangerous.

528
00:27:39,367 --> 00:27:41,512
I started Ava Corporation
to make people's lives better.

529
00:27:41,536 --> 00:27:42,745
I'm a good guy.

530
00:27:43,872 --> 00:27:47,709
Somewhere along the way, I started
using my genius to do terrible things.

531
00:27:47,792 --> 00:27:49,912
You no longer have
to do any of those things.

532
00:27:50,086 --> 00:27:51,606
The Bishop robot will do them for you.

533
00:27:52,380 --> 00:27:55,884
You're saying that robot I spoke to
on the phone will live my life?

534
00:27:56,676 --> 00:27:57,676
That is correct.

535
00:27:58,928 --> 00:28:02,557
Which means you are free
to fulfill your duty as a Time Master,

536
00:28:03,183 --> 00:28:05,602
with me, forever.

537
00:28:11,024 --> 00:28:13,109
Yo, who's hungry?

538
00:28:13,443 --> 00:28:16,529
It was a good day for hunting,
but a bad day for squirrels.

539
00:28:16,946 --> 00:28:20,074
And we have enough firewood
to last all night.

540
00:28:20,158 --> 00:28:21,659
Who knew Ava was part lumberjack?

541
00:28:21,743 --> 00:28:23,953
Yeah, apparently,
when it comes to my anxiety and wood,

542
00:28:24,370 --> 00:28:25,788
the wood's gonna lose every time.

543
00:28:25,872 --> 00:28:29,167
That's my girl. Come here.
Man, I have missed you.

544
00:28:31,502 --> 00:28:32,670
Mission accomplished.

545
00:28:33,421 --> 00:28:36,424
It was really nice not to have
to think about the team for a second.

546
00:28:36,507 --> 00:28:37,508
I missed you too,

547
00:28:37,592 --> 00:28:40,470
but I really needed
to get some aggression out, you know?

548
00:28:40,553 --> 00:28:42,305
Oh, yeah. Okay, I'll take that.

549
00:28:42,764 --> 00:28:45,391
- I was really crazy.
- I know, I've seen that.

550
00:28:45,850 --> 00:28:48,811
The captains look like happy campers,
and we got squirrel for dinner.

551
00:28:48,895 --> 00:28:49,938
A real win-win.

552
00:28:51,231 --> 00:28:52,732
Wait. Did you say "squirrel"?

553
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:55,485
Hey.

554
00:28:55,568 --> 00:28:58,696
That human experience we had,

555
00:28:59,906 --> 00:29:01,366
it was fun, wasn't it?

556
00:29:01,658 --> 00:29:03,201
Oh, yes, it was great fun.

557
00:29:03,701 --> 00:29:04,901
You know what I just realized?

558
00:29:05,662 --> 00:29:09,415
My favorite thing about being human
is being with other humans.

559
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:12,001
Me too.

560
00:29:32,647 --> 00:29:35,984
Hey, you can't just leave us in here.

561
00:29:37,318 --> 00:29:38,444
Where?

562
00:29:39,153 --> 00:29:41,281
Hey, hey, hey.

563
00:29:41,823 --> 00:29:43,157
It's all right.

564
00:29:43,241 --> 00:29:45,243
Sorry, it's my fault.

565
00:29:45,326 --> 00:29:46,327
Whose fault?

566
00:29:46,411 --> 00:29:49,914
A lad in my infantry unit.
He was my best friend from back home.

567
00:29:52,041 --> 00:29:53,293
Okay, hey.

568
00:29:53,376 --> 00:29:54,419
Tell me about him.

569
00:29:56,796 --> 00:29:59,048
You do like to talk a lot, don't you?

570
00:29:59,966 --> 00:30:00,967
I don't know.

571
00:30:02,385 --> 00:30:05,221
Somehow he just managed
to light up a room with a smile.

572
00:30:07,557 --> 00:30:09,392
He laughed at all of my terrible jokes.

573
00:30:10,727 --> 00:30:12,395
Never wrote me any letters,

574
00:30:13,896 --> 00:30:17,358
only the most...
the most delightful poetry.

575
00:30:20,695 --> 00:30:22,363
Sounds like you really cared about him.

576
00:30:28,286 --> 00:30:29,662
You loved him, didn't you?

577
00:30:32,123 --> 00:30:33,124
Hey.

578
00:30:33,207 --> 00:30:34,250
It's okay.

579
00:30:36,002 --> 00:30:37,795
Yeah. Yeah.

580
00:30:39,005 --> 00:30:40,465
I loved him.

581
00:30:41,841 --> 00:30:44,260
God forgive me,
I loved Alun more than anything.

582
00:30:46,763 --> 00:30:49,807
And it broke my heart
seeing how the war dimmed his light.

583
00:30:52,101 --> 00:30:56,564
But he was a changed man,
even before my cowardice got him killed.

584
00:30:56,647 --> 00:30:58,024
And seeing your brother,

585
00:30:59,192 --> 00:31:02,904
see, it reminds me of how he used to be.

586
00:31:04,238 --> 00:31:05,239
Hopeful.

587
00:31:08,743 --> 00:31:10,286
Yes, I loved Alun.

588
00:31:12,747 --> 00:31:13,998
And I failed him.

589
00:31:18,836 --> 00:31:23,633
You know, actually, Behrad,
the original version, it's a long story.

590
00:31:24,842 --> 00:31:26,511
He was a lot like you,

591
00:31:27,804 --> 00:31:30,098
a soldier who was forced
to grow up too fast.

592
00:31:33,768 --> 00:31:36,646
And I, um, I lost him because of that.

593
00:31:39,607 --> 00:31:42,110
For years,
there wasn't a day that went by

594
00:31:42,193 --> 00:31:44,612
when I didn't wish
that I had died instead of him.

595
00:31:46,948 --> 00:31:47,949
But I was lucky.

596
00:31:49,325 --> 00:31:51,411
I found these friends who had my back.

597
00:31:53,287 --> 00:31:56,374
And eventually I was able
to save my brother and my parents,

598
00:31:57,917 --> 00:32:01,671
and even make the world a better place
for a bunch of people I've never met.

599
00:32:05,007 --> 00:32:08,386
So, you're telling me that
a ragtag group of eccentrics,

600
00:32:08,469 --> 00:32:12,098
they helped you do all of that?

601
00:32:12,473 --> 00:32:13,891
Yeah, believe it or not.

602
00:32:15,726 --> 00:32:17,854
So, even though things
may feel hopeless right now,

603
00:32:19,981 --> 00:32:21,023
you've got us.

604
00:32:34,704 --> 00:32:35,997
Okay.

605
00:32:37,790 --> 00:32:39,125
Perfect.

606
00:32:44,839 --> 00:32:46,924
Don't worry. I'm coming for you guys.

607
00:32:50,303 --> 00:32:51,387
No.

608
00:32:57,518 --> 00:32:58,811
There you are.

609
00:32:58,895 --> 00:33:00,813
- Blessed saints.
- You found us.

610
00:33:00,938 --> 00:33:03,538
Good news is I think I found the parts
we need to fix the machine.

611
00:33:03,566 --> 00:33:04,984
Bravo, my boy, bravo!

612
00:33:05,693 --> 00:33:09,530
The bad news is,
it's 1986, we're in Chernobyl,

613
00:33:09,614 --> 00:33:11,532
and the meltdown is happening tonight.

614
00:33:17,830 --> 00:33:18,998
I don't understand.

615
00:33:19,081 --> 00:33:21,375
What is the significance
of this Chernobyl?

616
00:33:22,084 --> 00:33:24,754
By the 1930s, scientists
had figured out nuclear fission,

617
00:33:24,837 --> 00:33:28,049
which led to them creating
nuclear reactors to harness that energy.

618
00:33:28,132 --> 00:33:31,677
Lord in heaven, nuclear fission,
they learnt how to split the atom.

619
00:33:31,761 --> 00:33:35,056
Yeah, and by 1986,
there are a lot of nuclear reactors

620
00:33:35,139 --> 00:33:36,516
like the one here in Chernobyl.

621
00:33:37,141 --> 00:33:39,560
But tonight, a reactor explodes,

622
00:33:40,311 --> 00:33:42,813
and civilians won't be evacuated
for almost two days.

623
00:33:44,232 --> 00:33:46,734
People will die, and a lot more
will get radiation sickness.

624
00:33:46,943 --> 00:33:48,194
Hang on a second now.

625
00:33:48,277 --> 00:33:52,031
You said that the explosion
hasn't happened yet.

626
00:33:52,365 --> 00:33:53,365
Yeah.

627
00:33:54,116 --> 00:33:55,535
Whoa, whoa!

628
00:33:56,577 --> 00:33:58,788
Maybe this is why I am here.

629
00:33:59,830 --> 00:34:01,600
I might not have been able
to save Alun and the boys,

630
00:34:01,624 --> 00:34:05,253
but my divine purpose,
maybe this is it, God's will for me,

631
00:34:06,170 --> 00:34:07,505
to save people.

632
00:34:07,797 --> 00:34:09,274
- No, no. Hold on, buddy.
- Come back!

633
00:34:09,298 --> 00:34:11,926
Hey, hey.
Look, I'm all for hacking history,

634
00:34:12,009 --> 00:34:13,946
but if we make that big
of a change to the timeline,

635
00:34:13,970 --> 00:34:16,013
that killer <i>Wa verider</i>
will be right on top of us.

636
00:34:16,097 --> 00:34:17,533
It would be worth it
if we can save some lives.

637
00:34:17,557 --> 00:34:19,559
Yes, we must save lives.

638
00:34:20,935 --> 00:34:23,271
Okay, fine. How do we alert people?

639
00:34:23,646 --> 00:34:25,648
I think I know how. Come on.

640
00:34:26,440 --> 00:34:27,608
Okay.

641
00:34:38,995 --> 00:34:41,455
Now that there's a robot version
of me living my life,

642
00:34:43,666 --> 00:34:44,792
I'm expendable.

643
00:34:46,961 --> 00:34:48,421
I'm a nobody now.

644
00:34:49,130 --> 00:34:51,424
The life of a Time Master
is one of anonymity,

645
00:34:51,507 --> 00:34:53,301
and in some sense, expendability.

646
00:34:53,384 --> 00:34:54,927
About as far back as I can remember,

647
00:34:55,011 --> 00:34:58,139
I've always wanted
to help the world with my genius.

648
00:34:59,056 --> 00:35:03,311
I was convinced the world needed me.

649
00:35:03,811 --> 00:35:06,355
You are helping the world
as a Time Master,

650
00:35:06,439 --> 00:35:09,108
and you'll start
by thoroughly eliminating the Legends.

651
00:35:10,192 --> 00:35:11,193
Right.

652
00:35:12,403 --> 00:35:13,404
The Legends.

653
00:35:14,864 --> 00:35:17,158
The folks who gave me
a chance to redeem myself

654
00:35:17,241 --> 00:35:19,160
after I tried to destroy the world.

655
00:35:22,246 --> 00:35:23,247
Yeah, there it is.

656
00:35:23,539 --> 00:35:25,082
Fantastic work again, my boy.

657
00:35:25,166 --> 00:35:26,977
- I'll keep an eye out.
- Good you speak Russian.

658
00:35:27,001 --> 00:35:30,296
Yes, well, I picked it up working in
a lab with some Russian scientists.

659
00:35:30,421 --> 00:35:31,756
Lovely gentlemen, you know.

660
00:35:31,839 --> 00:35:33,599
But I never thought
I'd be using it for this.

661
00:35:33,883 --> 00:35:35,134
Okay, let's try this.

662
00:35:36,218 --> 00:35:37,928
- Right, go ahead.
- Okay.

663
00:36:04,288 --> 00:36:06,768
- Quickly, let's get out of here.
- Yes, let's get out of here.

664
00:36:21,055 --> 00:36:22,598
It worked! Look, everybody's leaving!

665
00:36:22,682 --> 00:36:24,534
Yeah, but we won't have time
to run back and warn the gang

666
00:36:24,558 --> 00:36:25,827
before that <i>Wa verider</i> shows up.

667
00:36:25,851 --> 00:36:28,813
We will if we drive. Let's see
if I remember how to drive stick.

668
00:36:29,689 --> 00:36:31,023
Wow! Wow!

669
00:36:31,148 --> 00:36:33,234
Motorcars of the future
are truly fascinating.

670
00:36:33,484 --> 00:36:34,485
Come on.

671
00:36:38,906 --> 00:36:40,991
Now, will you look at that?

672
00:36:41,367 --> 00:36:42,928
We took a little break
from leading the team,

673
00:36:42,952 --> 00:36:44,620
and everything turned out fine.

674
00:36:44,954 --> 00:36:46,831
Yeah. The kids are all grown up.

675
00:36:50,292 --> 00:36:52,002
Hey, what's up with those two?

676
00:36:53,129 --> 00:36:56,340
I think they got into a fight
with a gooseberry bush and lost.

677
00:37:00,010 --> 00:37:04,432
- You don't think that they...
- No.

678
00:37:07,685 --> 00:37:09,311
Any sign of them yet?

679
00:37:09,437 --> 00:37:12,690
No, I hope they don't
run into any dinosaurs.

680
00:37:14,734 --> 00:37:16,736
Hey, guys, listen.

681
00:37:16,819 --> 00:37:19,113
What's that weird noise?

682
00:37:20,114 --> 00:37:21,449
According to my audio analysis,

683
00:37:21,532 --> 00:37:23,552
it's a straight-four engine
with manual transmission.

684
00:37:23,576 --> 00:37:26,216
And the squeaking noise suggests
there's a problem with the clutch.

685
00:37:34,962 --> 00:37:36,672
Guess we're not gonna
see those dinosaurs.

686
00:37:40,342 --> 00:37:41,635
Please get the hell out of here.

687
00:37:41,719 --> 00:37:43,721
We're in 1986,
just outside of Chernobyl.

688
00:37:43,888 --> 00:37:44,889
- What?
- What?

689
00:37:44,972 --> 00:37:46,974
The meltdown's gonna happen
in about 20 minutes.

690
00:37:47,057 --> 00:37:48,702
We did make
a small change to the timeline.

691
00:37:48,726 --> 00:37:50,102
Hold on. What did you guys do?

692
00:37:50,186 --> 00:37:52,813
We broadcast a message
from a military base

693
00:37:52,897 --> 00:37:54,791
informing everyone
that the meltdown was imminent,

694
00:37:54,815 --> 00:37:56,175
that they should flee immediately.

695
00:37:56,442 --> 00:37:59,361
I wasn't in good conscience gonna leave
without doing something, was I?

696
00:37:59,445 --> 00:38:02,281
Okay. While I definitely
understand, you guys,

697
00:38:02,364 --> 00:38:04,700
that's not a small change
to the timeline.

698
00:38:04,784 --> 00:38:06,994
You've potentially affected
thousands of lives...

699
00:38:07,077 --> 00:38:09,163
Yeah, and you just
put a huge target on our backs.

700
00:38:11,665 --> 00:38:14,105
We have another disturbance
in the timeline, Captain.

701
00:38:14,585 --> 00:38:15,795
Where to, Gideon?

702
00:38:15,961 --> 00:38:19,381
1986. The city of Chernobyl
in the Soviet Union.

703
00:38:19,548 --> 00:38:21,383
Guess who's causing the disturbance?

704
00:38:21,717 --> 00:38:22,885
I doubt that's necessary.

705
00:38:23,093 --> 00:38:25,374
Because the Legends
wreak havoc wherever they go.

706
00:38:25,554 --> 00:38:27,240
And you can finally end it,
once and for all,

707
00:38:27,264 --> 00:38:28,891
by eliminating them for good.

708
00:38:28,974 --> 00:38:32,603
Didn't you say rash actions
add more ripples to the timeline?

709
00:38:32,770 --> 00:38:35,105
Fortunately, we're at
an opportune moment in history.

710
00:38:35,523 --> 00:38:37,358
Any ripple effect you cause
will be negligible

711
00:38:37,441 --> 00:38:39,777
due to its close proximity
to such a catastrophic event.

712
00:38:41,070 --> 00:38:43,489
Are you ready to save the timeline
from the Legends, Captain?

713
00:38:58,504 --> 00:38:59,505
What's that noise?

714
00:38:59,588 --> 00:39:01,173
- It's the <i>Wa verider.</i>
- Oh, man!

715
00:39:01,257 --> 00:39:03,259
You guys need to go
fix that time machine. Now!

716
00:39:03,342 --> 00:39:04,718
We need to put out this fire.

717
00:39:04,802 --> 00:39:07,513
Be ready. We have no idea
who or what is on that ship.

718
00:39:08,722 --> 00:39:11,559
Now, if we can wire
the magnetic components together...

719
00:39:11,642 --> 00:39:15,896
We can bridge the electric current
from the compass to the ignition coil

720
00:39:15,980 --> 00:39:17,314
and start the machine.

721
00:39:17,815 --> 00:39:21,193
Absolutely fantastic work, young lady.
Fantastic! Very well.

722
00:39:21,819 --> 00:39:24,405
Hey, Zari.
I've been doing a lot of thinking.

723
00:39:25,322 --> 00:39:26,866
You... you wanna talk right now?

724
00:39:27,366 --> 00:39:28,552
If I don't get this off my chest,

725
00:39:28,576 --> 00:39:30,336
I won't be able
to think about anything else.

726
00:39:31,078 --> 00:39:32,162
Go for it. I got it!

727
00:39:37,001 --> 00:39:38,669
Yes, I want to live
in the Totem with you.

728
00:39:39,712 --> 00:39:40,712
You do?

729
00:39:40,963 --> 00:39:44,216
Are you sure? You haven't had
a lot of time to think about it.

730
00:39:44,300 --> 00:39:45,342
You don't get it.

731
00:39:45,426 --> 00:39:48,220
It doesn't matter where I go,
as long as I'm with you.

732
00:39:52,975 --> 00:39:54,560
Uh, yes, we need more wire.

733
00:39:54,643 --> 00:39:57,646
Mmm. I got it! This is very us.

734
00:39:57,730 --> 00:39:59,398
- This is so us.
- Yeah.

735
00:40:05,446 --> 00:40:07,072
Ah! Here it comes.

736
00:40:07,531 --> 00:40:08,741
Not if I stop it first.

737
00:40:09,241 --> 00:40:10,951
Come on. We've gotta go. Let's go!

738
00:40:14,413 --> 00:40:16,224
We're right above
the Legends, Captain.

739
00:40:16,248 --> 00:40:17,791
Only you can engage our weapons.

740
00:40:17,875 --> 00:40:20,586
It's time to prove to me
that you're the man I know you are.

741
00:40:25,090 --> 00:40:27,176
Oh, I'm sorry, Gideon,
I just can't do it!

742
00:40:27,259 --> 00:40:29,637
I just can't kill the Legends.

743
00:40:30,179 --> 00:40:33,390
Sure, they used me,
but they used me to do good.

744
00:40:33,474 --> 00:40:36,235
Please return to your seat
and focus on the mission, Captain.

745
00:40:36,435 --> 00:40:38,538
So one of these days, you're gonna
shoot me out the cargo bay,

746
00:40:38,562 --> 00:40:39,980
like you did to Time Mistress Ava.

747
00:40:40,064 --> 00:40:42,191
And I'd rather die
with a little more dignity.

748
00:40:42,441 --> 00:40:43,627
There's nowhere to run!

749
00:40:43,651 --> 00:40:45,235
You're wrong about that, Gideon!

750
00:40:45,319 --> 00:40:47,446
No, do not go into Section A2.

751
00:40:58,999 --> 00:41:01,085
That thing I just said
about dying with dignity...

752
00:41:02,670 --> 00:41:03,671
I lied.

753
00:41:05,673 --> 00:41:06,757
Dignity is overrated.

754
00:41:17,393 --> 00:41:18,477
Yes!

755
00:41:27,820 --> 00:41:28,821
What is that?

756
00:41:30,030 --> 00:41:31,532
It's coming straight for us.

757
00:41:31,615 --> 00:41:32,783
Is that someone on a toilet?

758
00:41:32,866 --> 00:41:33,909
Who cares? Let's go!

759
00:41:37,121 --> 00:41:38,330
Somebody press the red button.

760
00:41:38,497 --> 00:41:40,577
Whoever it is,
they're gonna land right on top of us.

761
00:41:49,174 --> 00:41:50,884
Oh, crap!

